[[sn:Samurai retainers]]
[[en:Samurai retainers]]
[[ja:武家奉公人]]

{{Citation needed|date=June 28, 2015, 13:33 (UTC)}}
[[Image:Ashigalu.jpg|thumb|300px|{{ill|Ishikawa Ryusen|ja|石川流宣|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'s illustration of a servant in ''{{ill|Yamato Kōsaku Eshō|ja|大和耕作絵抄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''.]]
[[File:Jidai Matsuri 2009 143.jpg|300px|thumbnail|Servants during the {{ill|Jidai Matsuri|ja|時代祭|qq=draft|qq=draft}}]]

'''Buke Hōkōnin''' (武家奉公人) refers to retainers of peasant or townsman origin who served the {{ill|buke|ja|武家|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (samurai class). During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, such retainers were commonly referred to as simply {{ill|hōkōnin|ja|奉公人|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, including samurai retainers who served their masters. These individuals primarily handled subordinate tasks for warriors, such as carrying equipment, taking care of horses, and preparing meals. In some regions, they also participated in military service. By the Edo period, the term exclusively referred to non-samurai retainers like ''chūgen'' (中間) and ''komono'' (小者).

== Types ==
''Buke Hōkōnin'' included Ranks such as ''wakatō,'' ''chūgen,'' and ''komono.'' However, the terms varied significantly depending on the region, domain, and household, and distinctions were not rigid. For example, ''buke hōkōnin'' could sometimes include {{ill|ashigaru|ja|足軽|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, with their status either being below or above ''wakatō'' depending on the explanation.<ref name="kotowaka">{{cite web|url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E8%8B%A5%E5%85%9A-153895|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240713000056/https://kotobank.jp/word/%E8%8B%A5%E5%85%9A-153895|title=Wakatō|publisher=Kotobank|archive-date=2024-07-13|access-date=2024-07-24}}</ref> Thus, the descriptions of ''wakatō,'' ''chūgen,'' and ''komono'' below are provided as general references.

=== Wakatō (若党) ===
The term ''wakatō'' appears in the text of {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|qq=draft|qq=draft}}’s 1591 temporary {{ill|class system edict|ja|身分統制令|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, where "samurai" (侍) is thought to refer to ''wakatō.''<ref name="asukak">{{Cite journal|author=Asuka Kato|url=https://doi.org/10.24707/aichikenshikenkyu.5.0_123|title=On Toyotomi Hideyoshi's Edict of 1591|journal=Aichi Historical Studies|volume=5|pages=123–130|doi=10.24707/aichikenshikenkyu.5.0_123}}</ref><ref name="kotomibun">{{cite web|url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E8%BA%AB%E5%88%86%E7%B5%B1%E5%88%B6%E4%BB%A4-872534|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231203072152/https://kotobank.jp/word/%E8%BA%AB%E5%88%86%E7%B5%B1%E5%88%B6%E4%BB%A4-872534|title=Class System Edict|publisher=Kotobank|archive-date=2023-12-03|access-date=2024-07-24}}</ref> The term originally referred to young retainers, as indicated in ''{{ill|Teijō Zatsuki|ja|貞丈雑記|qq=draft|qq=draft}},'' which states: "Wakatō refers to young samurai." Over time, however, it came to denote lower-Ranking samurai retainers.<ref>''World Encyclopedia,'' Hitachi Digital Heibonsha, 1998.</ref>

In the {{ill|Azuchi-Momoyama period|ja|安土桃山時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the Edo period, ''wakatō'' served as low-Ranking attendants who carried out errands and guarded their masters. They were also called ''wakatō samurai'' and wore {{ill|daishō|ja|大小|qq=draft|qq=draft}} swords along with {{ill|haori|ja|羽織|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|hakama|ja|袴|qq=draft|qq=draft}} while accompanying their masters. Their annual stipend was about three ryō and one koku, leading them to be colloquially called "three-one samurai."<ref name="ketteiban">''Definitive Edo Period Reference,'' Shin Jinbutsu Ōraisha, 1994, ASIN B00N4T23DQ.</ref>

=== Chūgen (中間) ===
''Chūgen'' were servants of non-samurai status, distinct from ''wakatō.'' They carried only one sword, often made of wood, and were prohibited from wearing silk garments. ''Chūgen'' were typically hired on a seasonal or one-time basis, often recruited through brokers in cities like {{ill|Edo|ja|江戸|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<br />
Some ''chūgen'' held special roles, such as hereditary retainers in certain domains, who were permitted to bear surnames and swords.<ref>''Legacy Collection,'' Yonezawa City Library.</ref>

=== Komono (小者) ===
''Komono'' were private servants who primarily performed miscellaneous tasks. They were also known as ''kobito'' or ''genan'' (下男). In the {{ill|Edo period}}, they assisted magistrates in arrest operations and were occasionally authorized to carry weapons like {{ill|jutte|ja|十手|qq=draft}}.<br />
During the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, ''komono'' served as battlefield assistants responsible for tasks like carrying supplies.

== Changes in the Bakumatsu Period ==
In the {{ill|Bakumatsu|ja|幕末|qq=draft|qq=draft}} period, both the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|ja|Tokugawa shogunate|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and feudal domains abolished traditional musketeer units and established modern {{ill|infantry|ja|歩兵|qq=draft|qq=draft}} or firearm units. Some of these units were composed of ''chūgen'' recruits, reflecting a return to the recruitment practices of the Sengoku period.

